1Ô∏è‚É£ Build the Application Locally

mkdir backend && cd backend
npm init -y
npm install express cors
//server.js

import express from "express";
import cors from "cors";

const app = express();
app.use(cors());

app.get("/", (req, res) => {
  res.send("Hello from AWS Backend!");
});

const PORT = process.env.PORT || 5000;
app.listen(PORT, () => console.log(`Server running on port ${PORT}`));
//Run locally:

node server.js
//üíª Frontend (React)
npx create-react-app frontend
cd frontend
npm run build

2Ô∏è‚É£ Create EC2 Instances

You need 2 backend EC2 instances and 1 frontend EC2 instance.

Steps:

Go to AWS Console ‚Üí EC2 ‚Üí Launch Instance

Choose Amazon Linux 2 or Ubuntu 22.04 LTS AMI

Select instance type: t2.micro (Free Tier)

Configure security group:

Allow HTTP (80) and SSH (22) inbound.

Create and download a key pair (.pem) to connect via SSH.

3Ô∏è‚É£ Deploy Backend on EC2

//SSH into the backend instance:

ssh -i your-key.pem ec2-user@<instance-public-ip>

//Install Node.js:

sudo apt update
sudo apt install -y nodejs npm

//Clone or upload your backend code:
git clone <your-repo-url> backend
cd backend
npm install
node server.js
//Test in browser:
http://<EC2-Public-IP>:5000

4Ô∏è‚É£ Deploy Frontend on EC2
Launch another EC2 instance for frontend.
SSH into it and install Nginx:
sudo apt update
sudo apt install -y nginx
Copy your React build folder to /var/www/html:
sudo rm -rf /var/www/html/*
sudo cp -r build/* /var/www/html/
sudo systemctl restart nginx
Visit frontend IP in browser ‚Äî you should see your React app!


Connect Frontend to Load Balancer

In your React app (e.g., .env file):

REACT_APP_API_URL=http://my-app-alb-123456789.us-east-1.elb.amazonaws.com
